# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: compression-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:compression-physics/area] The area of a shape can be measured by comparing the shape to squares of a fixed size.
[src:compression-physics/area] In the International System of Units (SI), the standard unit of area is the square metre (written as m2), which is the area of a square whose sides are one metre long.
[src:compression-physics/area] A shape with an area of three square metres would have the same area as three such squares.
[src:compression-physics/area] In mathematics, the unit square is defined to have area one, and the area of any other shape or surface is a dimensionless real number.
[src:compression-physics/area] There are several well-known formulas for the areas of simple shapes such as triangles, rectangles, and circles.
[src:compression-physics/area] Using these formulas, the area of any polygon can be found by dividing the polygon into triangles.
[src:compression-physics/area] For shapes with curved boundaries, calculus is usually required to compute the area.
[src:compression-physics/area] In all, the problem of determining the area of plane figures was a major motivation for the historical development of calculus.
[src:compression-physics/area] For a solid shape such as a sphere, cone, or cylinder, the area of its boundary surface is called the surface area.
[src:compression-physics/area] Formulas for the surface areas of simple shapes were computed by the ancient Greeks, but computing the surface area of a more complicated shape usually requires multivariable calculus.
[src:compression-physics/area] Area plays an important role in modern mathematics.
[src:compression-physics/area] In addition to its obvious importance in geometry and calculus, area is related to the definition of determinants in linear algebra, and is a basic property of surfaces in differential geometry.
[src:compression-physics/area] In analysis, the area of a subset of the plane is defined using Lebesgue measure, though not every subset is measurable if one supposes the axiom of choice.
[src:compression-physics/area] In general, area in higher mathematics is seen as a special case of volume for two-dimensional regions.
[src:compression-physics/area] Area can be defined through the use of axioms, defining it as a function of a collection of certain plane figures to the set of real numbers.
[src:compression-physics/area] It can be proved that such a function exists.
[src:compression-physics/area] An approach to defining what is meant by "area" is through axioms.
[src:compression-physics/area] It can be proved that such an area function actually exists.
[src:compression-physics/area] Every unit of length has a corresponding unit of area, namely the area of a square with the given side length.
[src:compression-physics/area] Thus areas can be measured in square metres (m2), square centimetres (cm2), square millimetres (mm2), square kilometres (km2), square feet (ft2), square yards (yd2), square miles (mi2), and so forth.
[src:compression-physics/area] Algebraically, these units can be thought of as the squares of the corresponding length units.
[src:compression-physics/area] The SI unit of area is the square metre, which is considered an SI derived unit.
[src:compression-physics/area] This is equivalent to 6 million square millimetres.
[src:compression-physics/area] In non-metric units, the conversion between two square units is the square of the conversion between the corresponding length units.
[src:compression-physics/area] There are several other common units for area.
[src:compression-physics/area] Other uncommon metric units of area include the tetrad, the hectad, and the myriad.
[src:compression-physics/area] An acre is approximately 40% of a hectare.
[src:compression-physics/area] The barn is commonly used in describing the cross-sectional area of interaction in nuclear physics.
[src:compression-physics/area] In South Asia (mainly Indians), although the countries use SI units as official, many South Asians still use traditional units.
[src:compression-physics/area] Each administrative division has its own area unit, some of them have same names, but with different values.
[src:compression-physics/area] There is no official consensus about the traditional units values.
[src:compression-physics/area] Thus, the conversions between the SI units and the traditional units may have different results, depending on what reference that has been used.
[src:compression-physics/area] In the 5th century BCE, Hippocrates of Chios was the first to show that the area of a disk (the region enclosed by a circle) is proportional to the square of its diameter, as part of his quadrature of the lune of Hippocrates, but did not identify the constant of proportionality.
[src:compression-physics/area] Eudoxus of Cnidus, also in the 5th century BCE, also found that the area of a disk is proportional to its radius squared.
[src:compression-physics/area] Subsequently, Book I of Euclid's *Elements* dealt with equality of areas between two-dimensional figures.
[src:compression-physics/area] The mathematician Archimedes used the tools of Euclidean geometry to show that the area inside a circle is equal to that of a right triangle whose base has the length of the circle's circumference and whose height equals the circle's radius, in his book *Measurement of a Circle*.
[src:compression-physics/area] In 300 BCE Greek mathematician Euclid proved that the area of a triangle is half that of a parallelogram with the same base and height in his book *Elements of Geometry*.
[src:compression-physics/area] Heron of Alexandria found what is known as Heron's formula for the area of a triangle in terms of its sides, and a proof can be found in his book, *Metrica*, written around 60 CE.
[src:compression-physics/area] It has been suggested that Archimedes knew the formula over two centuries earlier, and since *Metrica* is a collection of the mathematical knowledge available in the ancient world, it is possible that the formula predates the reference given in that work.
[src:compression-physics/area] In 499 CE Aryabhata, a mathematician-astronomer from the classical age of Indian mathematics and Indian astronomy, expressed the area of a triangle as one-half the base times the height in the *Aryabhatiya*.
[src:compression-physics/area] A formula equivalent to Heron's was discovered by the Chinese independently of the Greeks.
[src:compression-physics/area] It was published in 1247 in *Shushu Jiuzhang* ("Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections"), written by Qin Jiushao.
[src:compression-physics/area] In the 7th century CE, Brahmagupta developed a formula, now known as Brahmagupta's formula, for the area of a cyclic quadrilateral (a quadrilateral inscribed in a circle) in terms of its sides.
[src:compression-physics/area] In 1842, the German mathematicians Carl Anton Bretschneider and Karl Georg Christian von Staudt independently found a formula, known as Bretschneider's formula, for the area of any quadrilateral.
[src:compression-physics/area] The development of Cartesian coordinates by René Descartes in the 17th century allowed the development of the surveyor's formula for the area of any polygon with known vertex locations by Gauss in the 19th century.
[src:compression-physics/area] The development of integral calculus in the late 17th century provided tools that could subsequently be used for computing more complicated areas, such as the area of an ellipse and the surface areas of various curved three-dimensional objects.
[src:compression-physics/area] where when *i* = *n* − 1, then *i* + 1 is expressed as modulus *n* and so refers to 0.
[src:compression-physics/area] The most basic area formula is the formula for the area of a rectangle.
[src:compression-physics/area] That is, the area of the rectangle is the length multiplied by the width.
[src:compression-physics/area] The formula for the area of a rectangle follows directly from the basic properties of area, and is sometimes taken as a definition or axiom.
[src:compression-physics/area] On the other hand, if geometry is developed before arithmetic, this formula can be used to define multiplication of real numbers.
[src:compression-physics/area] Most other simple formulas for area follow from the method of dissection.
[src:compression-physics/area] This involves cutting a shape into pieces, whose areas must sum to the area of the original shape.
[src:compression-physics/area] For an example, any parallelogram can be subdivided into a trapezoid and a right triangle, as shown in figure to the left.
[src:compression-physics/area] If the triangle is moved to the other side of the trapezoid, then the resulting figure is a rectangle.
[src:compression-physics/area] However, the same parallelogram can also be cut along a diagonal into two congruent triangles, as shown in the figure to the right.
[src:compression-physics/area] It follows that the area of each triangle is half the area of the parallelogram: $A={\frac {1}{2}}bh{\text{ (triangle).}}$ Similar arguments can be used to find area formulas for the trapezoid as well as more complicated polygons.
[src:compression-physics/area] The formula for the area of a circle (more properly called the area enclosed by a circle or the area of a disk) is based on a similar method.
[src:compression-physics/area] Given a circle of radius *r*, it is possible to partition the circle into sectors, as shown in the figure to the right.
[src:compression-physics/area] Each sector is approximately triangular in shape, and the sectors can be rearranged to form an approximate parallelogram.
[src:compression-physics/area] The height of this parallelogram is *r*, and the width is half the circumference of the circle, or π*r*.
[src:compression-physics/area] Though the dissection used in this formula is only approximate, the error becomes smaller and smaller as the circle is partitioned into more and more sectors.
[src:compression-physics/area] The limit of the areas of the approximate parallelograms is exactly π*r*2, which is the area of the circle.
[src:compression-physics/area] This argument is actually a simple application of the ideas of calculus.
[src:compression-physics/area] In ancient times, the method of exhaustion was used in a similar way to find the area of the circle, and this method is now recognized as a precursor to integral calculus.
[src:compression-physics/area] Most basic formulas for surface area can be obtained by cutting surfaces and flattening them out (see: developable surfaces).
[src:compression-physics/area] For example, if the side surface of a cylinder (or any prism) is cut lengthwise, the surface can be flattened out into a rectangle.
[src:compression-physics/area] Similarly, if a cut is made along the side of a cone, the side surface can be flattened out into a sector of a circle, and the resulting area computed.
[src:compression-physics/area] The formula for the surface area of a sphere is more difficult to derive: because a sphere has nonzero Gaussian curvature, it cannot be flattened out.
[src:compression-physics/area] The formula for the surface area of a sphere was first obtained by Archimedes in his work *On the Sphere and Cylinder*.
[src:compression-physics/area] As with the formula for the area of a circle, any derivation of this formula inherently uses methods similar to calculus.
[src:compression-physics/area] To find the bounded area between two quadratic functions, we first subtract one from the other, writing the difference as $f(x)-g(x)=ax^{2}+bx+c=a(x-\alpha )(x-\beta )$ where *f*(*x*) is the quadratic upper bound and *g*(*x*) is the quadratic lower bound.
[src:compression-physics/area] By the area integral formulas above and Vieta's formula, we can obtain that $A={\frac {(b^{2}-4ac)^{3/2}}{6a^{2}}}={\frac {a}{6}}(\beta -\alpha )^{3},\qquad a\neq 0.$ The above remains valid if one of the bounding functions is linear instead of quadratic.
[src:compression-physics/area] The above calculations show how to find the areas of many common shapes.
[src:compression-physics/area] The areas of irregular (and thus arbitrary) polygons can be calculated using the "Surveyor's formula" (shoelace formula).
[src:compression-physics/area] and equality holds if and only if the curve is a circle.
[src:compression-physics/area] Thus a circle has the largest area of any closed figure with a given perimeter.
[src:compression-physics/area] At the other extreme, a figure with given perimeter *L* could have an arbitrarily small area, as illustrated by a rhombus that is "tipped over" arbitrarily far so that two of its angles are arbitrarily close to 0° and the other two are arbitrarily close to 180°.
[src:compression-physics/area] For a circle, the ratio of the area to the circumference (the term for the perimeter of a circle) equals half the radius *r*.
[src:compression-physics/area] This can be seen from the area formula *πr*2 and the circumference formula 2*πr*.
[src:compression-physics/area] The area of a regular polygon is half its perimeter times the apothem (where the apothem is the distance from the center to the nearest point on any side).
[src:compression-physics/area] Doubling the edge lengths of a polygon multiplies its area by four, which is two (the ratio of the new to the old side length) raised to the power of two (the dimension of the space the polygon resides in).
[src:compression-physics/area] But if the one-dimensional lengths of a fractal drawn in two dimensions are all doubled, the spatial content of the fractal scales by a power of two that is not necessarily an integer.
[src:compression-physics/area] This power is called the fractal dimension of the fractal.
[src:compression-physics/area] There are an infinitude of lines that bisect the area of a triangle.
[src:compression-physics/area] Three of them are the medians of the triangle (which connect the sides' midpoints with the opposite vertices), and these are concurrent at the triangle's centroid; indeed, they are the only area bisectors that go through the centroid.
[src:compression-physics/area] Any line through a triangle that splits both the triangle's area and its perimeter in half goes through the triangle's incenter (the center of its incircle).
[src:compression-physics/area] There are either one, two, or three of these for any given triangle.
[src:compression-physics/area] Any line through the midpoint of a parallelogram bisects the area.
[src:compression-physics/area] All area bisectors of a circle or other ellipse go through the center, and any chords through the center bisect the area.
[src:compression-physics/area] In the case of a circle they are the diameters of the circle.
[src:compression-physics/area] Given a wire contour, the surface of least area spanning ("filling") it is a minimal surface.
[src:compression-physics/area] The question of the filling area of the Riemannian circle remains open.
[src:compression-physics/area] The circle has the largest area of any two-dimensional object having the same perimeter.
[src:compression-physics/area] A cyclic polygon (one inscribed in a circle) has the largest area of any polygon with a given number of sides of the same lengths.
[src:compression-physics/area] A version of the isoperimetric inequality for triangles states that the triangle of greatest area among all those with a given perimeter is equilateral.
[src:compression-physics/area] The triangle of largest area of all those inscribed in a given circle is equilateral; and the triangle of smallest area of all those circumscribed around a given circle is equilateral.
[src:compression-physics/area] The ratio of the area of the incircle to the area of an equilateral triangle, ${\frac {\pi }{3{\sqrt {3}}}}$ , is larger than that of any non-equilateral triangle.
[src:compression-physics/area] The ratio of the area to the square of the perimeter of an equilateral triangle, ${\frac {1}{12{\sqrt {3}}}},$ is larger than that for any other triangle.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] A **balloon** is a flexible membrane bag that can be inflated with a gas, such as helium, hydrogen, nitrous oxide, oxygen, or air.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] For special purposes, balloons can be filled with smoke, liquid water, granular media (e.g. sand, flour or rice), or light sources.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Modern-day balloons are made from materials such as rubber, latex, polychloroprene, or a nylon fabric, and can come in many different colors.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Some early balloons were made of dried animal bladders, such as the pig bladder.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Some balloons are used for decoration or entertainment, while others have practical purposes such as meteorology, medical treatment, military defense, or transportation.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] A balloon's properties, including its low density and low cost, have led to a wide range of applications.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The rubber balloon was invented by Michael Faraday in 1824, during experiments with various gases.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloons are used for decorating birthday parties, weddings, corporate functions, school events, and for other festive gatherings.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The most common types of balloon decor include arches, columns, centerpieces, balloon drops, sculptures, and balloon bouquets.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] With the increased aptitude for balloon twisting as well as balloon stacking, the rise of the deco-twister manifests itself as the combination of stacking techniques as well as twisting techniques to create unique and interesting balloon decor options.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Party balloons are mostly made of a natural latex tapped from rubber trees, and can be filled with air, helium, water, or any other suitable liquid or gas.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The rubber's elasticity makes the volume adjustable.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Often the term "party balloon" will refer to a twisting balloon or pencil balloon.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] These balloons are manipulated to create shapes and figures for parties and events, typically along with entertainment.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Filling the balloon with air can be done with the mouth, a manual or electric inflater (such as a hand pump), or with a source of compressed gas.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] When rubber or plastic balloons are filled with helium so that they float, they typically retain their buoyancy for only a day or so, sometimes longer.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The enclosed helium atoms escape through small pores in the latex which are larger than the helium atoms.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] However, some types of balloons are labelled "helium-grade".
[src:compression-physics/balloon] These balloons are often thicker and have less porosity.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloons filled with air usually hold their size and shape much longer, sometimes for up to a week.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] However, a rubber balloon eventually loses gas to the outside.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The process by which a substance or solute migrates from a region of high concentration, through a barrier or membrane, to a region of lower concentration is called diffusion.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The inside of balloons can be treated with a special gel (for instance, the polymer solution sold under the "Hi Float" brand) which coats the inside of the balloon to reduce the helium leakage, thus increasing float time to a week or longer.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Beginning in the late 1970s, some more expensive (and longer-lasting) foil balloons made of thin, unstretchable, less permeable metallised films such as Mylar (BoPET) started being produced.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] These balloons have attractive shiny reflective surfaces and are often printed with color pictures and patterns for gifts and parties.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The most important attributes of metallised nylon for balloons are its light weight, increasing buoyancy, and its ability to keep the helium gas from escaping for several weeks.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Foil balloons have been criticized for interfering with power lines.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloon artists are entertainers who twist and tie inflated tubular balloons into sculptures such as animals (see balloon modelling).
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The balloons used for sculpture are made of extra-stretchy rubber so that they can be twisted and tied without bursting.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Since the pressure required to inflate a balloon is inversely proportional to the diameter of the balloon, these tiny tubular balloons are extremely hard to inflate initially.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] A pump is usually used to inflate these balloons.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Decorators may use helium balloons to create balloon sculptures.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Usually the round shape of the balloon restricts these to simple arches or walls, but on occasion more ambitious "sculptures" have been attempted.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] It is also common to use balloons as table decorations for celebratory events.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloons can sometimes be modeled to form shapes of animals.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Table decorations normally appear with several balloons in each bouquet.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Ribbon is curled and added with a weight to keep the balloons from floating away.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] A decorative use for balloons is in balloon drops.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] In a balloon drop, a plastic bag or net filled with air-inflated balloons is suspended from a fixed height.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Once released, the balloons fall onto their target area below.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloon drops are commonly performed at New Year's Eve celebrations and at political rallies and conventions, but may also be performed at celebrations, including graduations and weddings.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Large ballon drops are a frequent feature at United States presidential nominating conventions.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] For decades, people have also celebrated with balloon releases.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] This practice has been discouraged by the balloon industry, as it has posed problematic for the environment and cities.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] In recent years, legislation such as the California Balloon Law has been enacted to enforce consumers and retailers to tether helium-filled foil (BoPET) balloons with a balloon weight.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] This ensures that the helium-filled balloons do not float into the atmosphere, which is potentially injurious to animals, the environment, and power lines.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Many states in the USA have banned balloon releases.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] It is becoming more common for balloons to be filled with air instead of helium, as air-filled balloons will not float into the atmosphere or deplete the earth's helium supply.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] There are numerous party games and school-related activities that can use air-filled balloons as opposed to helium balloons.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] When age-appropriate, these activities often include the added fun of blowing the balloons up.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] In many events, the balloons will contain prizes, and party-goers can pop the balloons to retrieve the items inside.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloons are used for publicity at major events.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Screen printing processes can be used to print designs and company logos onto the balloons.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Custom built printers inflate the balloon and apply ink with elastic qualities through a silk screen template.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] In January 2008, the Jewish Community Relations Council of New York organized a display of 4,200 red balloons outside the United Nations Headquarters.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Also in the 1950s at the start of the Cold War, activists in Western Europe uses balloons for propaganda purposes that would float east over Eastern Europe, which would release newspapers and pamphlets.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] In 2014, South Korean activists used the same balloon method to get information to those in North Korea.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Paolo Scannavino set the record of 11 for the most giant balloons entered in 2 minutes.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Water balloons are thin, small rubber balloons filled with a liquid, usually water, instead of a gas, and intended to be easily broken.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] They are usually used by children, who throw them at each other, trying to get each other wet, as a game, competition, or practical joke.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] By forcing water out the open end of a water balloon, it is possible to use it as a makeshift water gun.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Solar balloons are thin, large balloons filled with air that is heated by the sun in order to decrease its density to obtain lift.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloons are often deliberately released, creating a so-called balloon rocket.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloon rockets work because the elastic balloons contract on the air within them, and so when the mouth of the balloon is opened, the gas within the balloon is expelled out, and due to Newton's third law of motion, the balloon is propelled forward.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] This is the same way that a rocket works.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloons filled with hot air or a buoyant gas have been used as flying machines since the 18th century.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The earliest flights were made with hot air balloons using air heated with a flame, or hydrogen as the lifting gas.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Later, coal gas and later still helium were used.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] An unpowered balloon travels with the wind.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] A balloon which has an engine to propel it is called a dirigible balloon or airship.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Angioplasty is a surgical procedure in which very small balloons are inserted into blocked or partially blocked blood vessels near the heart.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Once in place, the balloon is inflated to clear or compress arterial plaque, and to stretch the walls of the vessel, thus preventing myocardial infarction.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] A small stent can be inserted at the angioplasty site to keep the vessel open after the balloon's removal.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloon catheters are catheters that have balloons at their tip to keep them from slipping out.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] For example, the balloon of a Foley catheter is inflated when the catheter is inserted into the urinary bladder and secures its position.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Insertion of balloons subsequently filled with air or liquid can be used to stop bleeding in hollow internal organs such as stomach or uterus.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Humans have intentionally filled bladders, especially actual animal bladders, with air since prehistory.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] In Ancient Greece, these had a number of recorded uses.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] By the 18th century, people were inflating balloons of cloth or canvas with hot air and sending it aloft, the Montgolfier brothers going so far as to experiment with first animals in 1782, and then, when altitude did not kill them, human beings in 1783.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The first hydrogen-filled gas balloon was flown in the 1790s.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] A century later the first hydrogen-filled weather balloons were launched in France.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The first modern rubber balloons on record were made by Michael Faraday in 1824.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] He used these to contain gasses he was experimenting with, especially hydrogen.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] By 1825 similar balloons were being sold by Thomas Hancock, but like Faraday's they came disassembled, as two circles of soft rubber.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The user was expected to lay the circles one on top of the other and rub their edges until the soft, gummy rubber stuck, leaving the powdered inner part loose for inflation.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Modern, preassembled balloons were being sold in the US by the early 20th century.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] There has been some environmental concern over metallised Mylar balloons, as they do not biodegrade or shred as rubber balloons do.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Release of these types of balloons into the atmosphere is considered harmful to the environment.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] This type of balloon can also conduct electricity on its surface and released foil balloons can become entangled in power lines and cause power outages.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Released balloons can land anywhere, including on nature reserves or other areas where they can pose a hazard to animals through ingestion or entanglement.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Because of the potential harm to wildlife and the effect of litter on the environment, some jurisdictions even legislate to control mass balloon releases.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Legislation proposed in Maryland, US, was named after Inky, a pygmy sperm whale who needed six operations after swallowing debris, the largest piece of which was a Mylar balloon.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The Balloon Council, a trade organization that represents the interests of balloon businesses, claims that there is no documentary evidence to suggest that the death of any sea mammal has been attributed to foil balloons as a sole cause, to date.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] In the United Kingdom, foil balloons sold at major theme parks and zoos have balloon weights attached to help prevent accidental release into the environment.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] When balloons eventually return to the ground, they begin the degradation process.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Latex balloons are the most used because of their ability to biodegrade.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The problem with this is that it can take at least 4 weeks to show substantial degradation of the polymer in the environment, and around 6 months in aquatic environments.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] This issue can have an effect on the wildlife on both land and in aquatic systems because animals will confuse deflated balloons as food, nesting material, or simply something to play with.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] When that happens, it can lead to negative effects for the animals.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] For example, a bird can use a deflated balloon as a component for its nest.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] When the eggs hatch, they will get tangled in the balloon and that can lead to death.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Anthony Andrady says that releases of latex balloons that descend into the sea pose a serious ingestion and/or entanglement hazard to marine animals because balloons exposed floating in seawater deteriorate much more slowly than those exposed in air.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloon manufacturers will often state that a latex balloon is perfectly safe to release into the environment as it is made from a natural substance and will biodegrade over time.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] A latex balloon can take up to a year to degrade if it lands in the sea and during this time it is possible for a marine animal to ingest the balloon and die from slow starvation if its digestive system is blocked.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] These recommendations have also been adopted by some industry professionals working with balloons in the fields of design and entertainment.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Traditionally balloons are manufactured from plastic.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] With the rise of worldwide awareness for environmental conservation, some balloon manufacturers started making balloons out of biodegradable materials, which are made entirely of natural recyclable rubber trees.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] These balloons manufacturing processes preserve the natural state of the material in such a way that allows it to degrade relatively quickly.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Another environmental problem with latex balloons is not the effects the balloons have on the environment once they are decomposed, but when they are being made.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] When latex is being produced, it produces greenhouse gases, such as CO2, CH4, N2O.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] This is becoming an increasing problem, especially in Thailand which is responsible for 35% of the world's natural rubber production.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] At the start of the 21st century, balloon recycling or reuse for other purposes was in its infancy.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] As of 2020, several balloon manufacturers have developed methods for effective balloon waste disposal, and some manufacturers use recycled balloons to produce other products, such as toys for pets.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Once inflated with regular, atmospheric air, the air inside the balloon will have a greater air pressure than the original atmospheric air pressure.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Air pressure, technically, is a measurement of the amount of collisions against a surface at any time.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] In the case of balloon, it is supposed to measure how many particles at any in any given time space collide with the wall of the balloon and bounce off.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Since this is nearly impossible to measure, air pressure seems to be more easily described as density.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The similarity comes from the idea that when there are more molecules in the same space, more of them will be heading towards a collision course with the wall.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The first concept of air pressure within a balloon that is necessary to know is that air pressures "try" to even out.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] With all the bouncing against the balloon wall (both interior and exterior) there will be a certain amount of expansion/contraction.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] As air pressure itself is a description of the total forces against an object, each of these forces, on the outside of the balloon, causes the balloon to contract a tiny bit, while the inside forces cause the balloon to expand.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] With this knowledge, one would immediately assume that a balloon with high air pressure inside would expand based on the high amount of internal forces, and vice versa.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] This would make the inside and outside air pressures equal.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Balloons have a certain elasticity to them that needs to be taken into account.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The act of stretching a balloon fills it with potential energy.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] When it is released, the potential energy is converted to kinetic energy and the balloon snaps back into its original position, though perhaps a little stretched out.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] When a balloon is filled with air, the balloon is being stretched.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] While the elasticity of the balloon causes tension that would have the balloon collapse, it is also being pushed back out by the constant bouncing of the internal air molecules.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] The internal air has to exert force not only to counteract the external air to keep the air pressures "even", but it also has to counteract the natural contraction of the balloon.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Therefore, it requires more air pressure (or force) than the air outside the balloon wall.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] Because of this, when helium balloons are left and they float higher, as atmospheric pressure decreases, the air inside it exerts more pressure than outside it so the balloon pops from tension.
[src:compression-physics/balloon] In some cases, the helium leaks out from pores and the balloon deflates, falling down.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] In structural engineering, **buckling** is the sudden change in shape (deformation) of a structural component under load, such as the bowing of a column under compression or the wrinkling of a plate under shear.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] If a structure is subjected to a gradually increasing load, when the load reaches a critical level, a member may suddenly change shape and the structure and component is said to have *buckled*.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Euler's critical load and Johnson's parabolic formula are used to determine the buckling stress of a column.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Buckling may occur even though the stresses that develop in the structure are well below those needed to cause failure in the material of which the structure is composed.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Further loading may cause significant and somewhat unpredictable deformations, possibly leading to complete loss of the member's load-carrying capacity.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] However, if the deformations that occur after buckling do not cause the complete collapse of that member, the member will continue to support the load that caused it to buckle.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] If the buckled member is part of a larger assemblage of components such as a building, any load applied to the buckled part of the structure beyond that which caused the member to buckle will be redistributed within the structure.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Some aircraft are designed for thin skin panels to continue carrying load even in the buckled state.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The ratio of the effective length of a column to the least radius of gyration of its cross section is called the slenderness ratio (sometimes expressed with the Greek letter lambda, λ).
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This ratio affords a means of classifying columns and their failure mode.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The slenderness ratio is important for design considerations.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] All the following are approximate values used for convenience.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] If the load on a column is applied through the center of gravity (centroid) of its cross section, it is called an axial load.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] A load at any other point in the cross section is known as an eccentric load.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] A short column under the action of an axial load will fail by direct compression before it buckles, but a long column loaded in the same manner will fail by springing suddenly outward laterally (buckling) in a bending mode.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The buckling mode of deflection is considered a failure mode, and it generally occurs before the axial compression stresses (direct compression) can cause failure of the material by yielding or fracture of that compression member.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] However, intermediate-length columns will fail by a combination of direct compressive stress and bending.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The theory of the behavior of columns was investigated in 1757 by mathematician Leonhard Euler.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] He derived the formula, termed Euler's critical load, that gives the maximum axial load that a long, slender, ideal column can carry without buckling.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] When the applied load reaches the Euler load, sometimes called the critical load, the column comes to be in a state of unstable equilibrium.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] At that load, the introduction of the slightest lateral force will cause the column to fail by suddenly "jumping" to a new configuration, and the column is said to have buckled.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This is what happens when a person stands on an empty aluminum can and then taps the sides briefly, causing it to then become instantly crushed (the vertical sides of the can may be understood as an infinite series of extremely thin columns).
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Examination of this formula reveals the following facts with regard to the load-bearing ability of slender columns.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] A conclusion from the above is that the buckling load of a column may be increased by changing its material to one with a higher modulus of elasticity (E), or changing the design of the column's cross section so as to increase its moment of inertia.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The latter can be done without increasing the weight of the column by distributing the material as far from the principal axis of the column's cross section as possible.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] For most purposes, the most effective use of the material of a column is that of a tubular section.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Another insight that may be gleaned from this equation is the effect of length on critical load.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Doubling the unsupported length of the column quarters the allowable load.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The restraint offered by the end connections of a column also affects its critical load.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] If the connections are perfectly rigid (not allowing rotation of its ends), the critical load will be four times that for a similar column where the ends are pinned (allowing rotation of its ends).
[src:compression-physics/buckling] where $\sigma =F/A$ is the stress that causes buckling in the column, and $l/r$ is the slenderness ratio.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Since structural columns are commonly of intermediate length, the Euler formula has little practical application for ordinary design.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Issues that cause deviation from the pure Euler column behaviour include imperfections in geometry of the column in combination with plasticity/non-linear stress strain behaviour of the column's material.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Consequently, a number of empirical column formulae have been developed that agree with test data, all of which embody the slenderness ratio.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Due to the uncertainty in the behavior of columns, for design, appropriate safety factors are introduced into these formulae.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] One such formula is the Perry Robertson formula which estimates the critical buckling load based on an assumed small initial curvature, hence an eccentricity of the axial load.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] where $F_{e}$ is the Euler maximum load and $F_{c}$ is the maximum compressive load.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This formula typically produces a conservative estimate of $F_{\max }$ .
[src:compression-physics/buckling] where g is the acceleration due to gravity, I is the second moment of area of the beam cross section, and B is the first zero of the Bessel function of the first kind of order −1/3, which is equal to 1.86635086...
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The stability of uniformly compressed thin-walled elastic rings has a long and well-established history, shaped by a number of significant contributions.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Most scholars agree that Levy's groundbreaking study from 1884 served as the theoretical foundation for further studies on the buckling of circular rings.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] A thin-walled ring of thickness t and mean radius R , subjected to a uniformly distributed radial load q , may in fact lose its initial circular configuration when the applied load reaches a critical value.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This instability phenomenon is characterized by the transition from the undeformed circular shape to a non-circular equilibrium configuration and represents one of the fundamental structural instability problems in elasticity theory.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Due to their close relationship to the popular Donnell approximations used in shell structure analysis , the governing equations for circular rings are very significant.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] A great deal of research of the predominant buckling modes of submarine and submersible pressure hulls, as well as other thin-walled cylindrical structures exposed to external pressure, as indicated in the engineering examples below, is based on similar assumptions.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] where E is the Young's modulus of the material and I is the second moment of area of the ring cross-section.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Following Levy's original derivation, the ring axis is commonly assumed to be inextensible.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] More recent studies, however, have investigated the influence of axis deformability on the buckling and post-buckling response of thin rings .
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Actually, accounting for the extensibility of the ring axis a more complete and physically consistent description of the post-buckling behaviour can be obtained.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] A plate is a 3-dimensional structure defined as having a width of comparable size to its length, with a thickness that is very small in comparison to its other two dimensions.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Similar to columns, thin plates experience out-of-plane buckling deformations when subjected to critical loads; however, contrasted to column buckling, plates under buckling loads can continue to carry loads, called local buckling.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This phenomenon is incredibly useful in numerous systems, as it allows systems to be engineered to provide greater loading capacities.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The buckling coefficient is influenced by the aspect of the specimen, a / ${b}$ , and the number of lengthwise curvatures.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] For an increasing number of such curvatures, the aspect ratio produces a varying buckling coefficient; but each relation provides a minimum value for each m .
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This minimum value can then be used as a constant, independent from both the aspect ratio and m .
[src:compression-physics/buckling] From the derived equations, it can be seen the close similarities between the critical stress for a column and for a plate.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] As the width b shrinks, the plate acts more like a column as it increases the resistance to buckling along the plate's width.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The increase of a allows for an increase of the number of sine waves produced by buckling along the length, but also increases the resistance from the buckling along the width.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This creates the preference of the plate to buckle in such a way to equal the number of curvatures both along the width and length.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Due to boundary conditions, when a plate is loaded with a critical stress and buckles, the edges perpendicular to the load cannot deform out-of-plane and will therefore continue to carry the stresses.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] As the loaded stress increases, the effective width continues to shrink; if the stresses on the ends ever reach the yield stress, the plate will fail.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This is what allows the buckled structure to continue supporting loadings.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] When the axial load over the critical load is plotted against the displacement, the fundamental path is shown.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] It demonstrates the plate's similarity to a column under buckling; however, past the buckling load, the fundamental path bifurcates into a secondary path that curves upward, providing the ability to be subjected to higher loads past the critical load.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Flexural-torsional buckling can be described as a combination of bending and twisting response of a member in compression.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Such a deflection mode must be considered for design purposes.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This mostly occurs in columns with "open" cross-sections and hence have a low torsional stiffness, such as channels, structural tees, double-angle shapes, and equal-leg single angles.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Circular cross sections do not experience such a mode of buckling.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] When a simply supported beam is loaded in bending, the top side is in compression, and the bottom side is in tension.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] If the beam is not supported in the lateral direction (i.e., perpendicular to the plane of bending), and the flexural load increases to a critical limit, the beam will experience a lateral deflection of the compression flange as it buckles locally.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The lateral deflection of the compression flange is restrained by the beam web and tension flange, but for an open section the twisting mode is more flexible, hence the beam both twists and deflects laterally in a failure mode known as *lateral-torsional buckling*.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] In wide-flange sections (with high lateral bending stiffness), the deflection mode will be mostly twisting in torsion.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] In narrow-flange sections, the bending stiffness is lower and the column's deflection will be closer to that of lateral bucking deflection mode.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The use of closed sections such as square hollow section will mitigate the effects of lateral-torsional buckling by virtue of their high torsional stiffness.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The result is the same for all unit systems.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The buckling strength of a member is less than the elastic buckling strength of a structure if the material of the member is stressed beyond the elastic material range and into the non-linear (plastic) material behavior range.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] When the compression load is near the buckling load, the structure will bend significantly and the material of the column will diverge from a linear stress-strain behavior.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The stress-strain behavior of materials is not strictly linear even below the yield point, hence the modulus of elasticity decreases as stress increases, and significantly so as the stresses approach the material's yield strength.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This reduced material rigidity reduces the buckling strength of the structure and results in a buckling load less than that predicted by the assumption of linear elastic behavior.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] A more accurate approximation of the buckling load can be had by the use of the tangent modulus of elasticity, Et, which is less than the elastic modulus, in place of the elastic modulus of elasticity.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The tangent is equal to the elastic modulus and then decreases beyond the proportional limit.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The tangent modulus is a line drawn tangent to the stress-strain curve at a particular value of strain (in the elastic section of the stress-strain curve, the tangent modulus is equal to the elastic modulus).
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Plots of the tangent modulus of elasticity for a variety of materials are available in standard references.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Sections that are made up of flanged plates such as a channel, can still carry load in the corners after the flanges have locally buckled.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Crippling is failure of the complete section.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Because of the thin skins typically used in aerospace applications, skins may buckle at low load levels.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] However, once buckled, instead of being able to transmit shear forces, they are still able to carry load through *diagonal tension* (DT) stresses in the web.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This results in a non-linear behaviour in the load carrying behaviour of these details.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The ratio of the actual load to the load at which buckling occurs is known as the *buckling ratio* of a sheet.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] High buckling ratios may lead to excessive wrinkling of the sheets which may then fail through yielding of the wrinkles.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Although they may buckle, thin sheets are designed to not permanently deform and return to an unbuckled state when the applied loading is removed.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Repeated buckling may lead to fatigue failures.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Sheets under diagonal tension are supported by stiffeners that as a result of sheet buckling carry a distributed load along their length, and may in turn result in these structural members failing under buckling.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Thicker plates may only partially form a diagonal tension field and may continue to carry some of the load through shear.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This is known as *incomplete diagonal tension* (IDT).
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This behavior was studied by Wagner and these beams are sometimes known as Wagner beams.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Diagonal tension may also result in a pulling force on any fasteners such as rivets that are used to fasten the web to the supporting members.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Fasteners and sheets must be designed to resist being pulled off their supports.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] If a column is loaded suddenly and then the load released, the column can sustain a much higher load than its static (slowly applied) buckling load.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This can happen in a long, unsupported column used as a drop hammer.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The duration of compression at the impact end is the time required for a stress wave to travel along the column to the other (free) end and back down as a relief wave.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Maximum buckling occurs near the impact end at a wavelength much shorter than the length of the rod, and at a stress many times the buckling stress of a statically loaded column.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] where $\sigma$ is the impact stress, L is the length of the rod, c is the elastic wave speed, and h is the smaller lateral dimension of a rectangular rod.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Because the buckle wavelength depends only on $\sigma$ and h , this same formula holds for thin cylindrical shells of thickness h .
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Often it is very difficult to determine the exact buckling load in complex structures using the Euler formula, due to the difficulty in determining the constant K.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Therefore, maximum buckling load is often approximated using energy conservation and referred to as an energy method in structural analysis.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The first step in this method is to assume a displacement mode and a function that represents that displacement.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] This function must satisfy the most important boundary conditions, such as displacement and rotation.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The more accurate the displacement function, the more accurate the result.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] The method assumes that the system (the column) is a conservative system in which energy is not dissipated as heat, hence the energy added to the column by the applied external forces is stored in the column in the form of strain energy.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] In this method, there are two equations used (for small deformations) to approximate the "strain" energy (the potential energy stored as elastic deformation of the structure) and "applied" energy (the work done on the system by external forces).
[src:compression-physics/buckling] where $w(x)$ is the displacement function and the subscripts x and $xx$ refer to the first and second derivatives of the displacement.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Using the concept of *total potential energy*, V , it is possible to identify four fundamental forms of buckling found in structural models with one degree of freedom.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] We start by expressing $V=U-P\Delta$ where U is the strain energy stored in the structure, P is the applied *conservative* load and $\Delta$ is the distance moved by P in its direction.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] These four forms of elastic buckling are the *saddle-node bifurcation* or *limit point*; the *supercritical* or *stable-symmetric* bifurcation; the *subcritical* or *unstable-symmetric* bifurcation; and the *transcritical* or *asymmetric* bifurcation.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] All but the first of these examples is a form of *pitchfork bifurcation*.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Simple models for each of these types of buckling behaviour are shown in the figures below, along with the associated bifurcation diagrams.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] A conventional bicycle wheel consists of a thin rim kept under high compressive stress by the (roughly normal) inward pull of a large number of spokes.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] It can be considered as a loaded column that has been bent into a circle.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] If spoke tension is increased beyond a safe level or if part of the rim is subject to a certain lateral force, the wheel spontaneously fails into a characteristic saddle shape (sometimes called a "taco" or a "pringle") like a three-dimensional Euler column.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] If this is a purely elastic deformation the rim will resume its proper plane shape if spoke tension is reduced or a lateral force from the opposite direction is applied.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Buckling is a failure mode in pavement materials, primarily with concrete, since asphalt is more flexible.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Radiant heat from the sun is absorbed in the road surface, causing it to expand, forcing adjacent pieces to push against each other.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] If the stress is sufficient, the pavement can lift and crack without warning.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Traversing a buckled section can be jarring to automobile drivers, described as running over a speed hump at highway speeds.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Similarly, rail tracks also expand when heated, and can fail by buckling, a phenomenon called **sun kink**.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] It is more common for rails to move laterally, often pulling the underlying ties (sleepers) along.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Sun kink can lead to railroads drastically reducing the speed of trains, leading to delays and cancellations.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Intensifying heat waves due to climate change doubled the number of hours of heat related delays in 2023, compared to 2018.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Pipes and pressure vessels subject to external overpressure and implosion, caused for example by steam cooling within the pipe and condensing into water with subsequent massive pressure drop, risk buckling due to compressive hoop stresses.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Design rules for calculation of the required wall thickness or reinforcement rings are given in various piping and pressure vessel codes.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Buckling is a major failure mode in submarine and submersible hulls.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] Aerothermal heating can lead to buckling of surface panels on super- and hypersonic aerospace vehicles such as high-speed aircraft, rockets and reentry vehicles.
[src:compression-physics/buckling] If buckling is caused by aerothermal loads, the situation can be further complicated by enhanced heat transfer in areas where the structure deforms towards the flow-field.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] The **bulk modulus** ( K or B or k ) of a substance is a measure of the resistance of a substance to bulk compression.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] It is defined as the ratio of the infinitesimal pressure increase to the resulting *relative* decrease of the volume.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] Other moduli describe the material's response (strain) to other kinds of stress: the shear modulus describes the response to shear stress and Young's modulus describes the response to normal (lengthwise stretching) stress.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] For a fluid, only the bulk modulus is meaningful.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] For a complex anisotropic solid such as wood or paper, these three moduli do not contain enough information to describe its behaviour, and one must use the full generalized Hooke's law.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] The reciprocal of the bulk modulus at fixed temperature is called the isothermal compressibility.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] where P is pressure, V is the initial volume of the substance, and $dP/dV$ denotes the derivative of pressure with respect to volume.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] where $\rho$ is the initial density and $dP/d\rho$ denotes the derivative of pressure with respect to density.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] The inverse of the bulk modulus gives a substance's compressibility.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] Generally, the bulk modulus is defined at constant temperature as the isothermal bulk modulus, but can also be defined at constant entropy as the adiabatic bulk modulus.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] Strictly speaking, the bulk modulus is a thermodynamic quantity, and in order to specify a bulk modulus it is necessary to specify how the pressure varies during compression: constant-temperature (isothermal $K_{T}$ ), constant-entropy (isentropic $K_{S}$ ), and other variations are possible.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] Such distinctions are especially relevant for gases.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] where $\gamma$ is the heat capacity ratio.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] When the gas is not ideal, these equations give only an approximation of the bulk modulus.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] In solids, $K_{S}$ and $K_{T}$ have very similar values.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] Solids can also sustain transverse waves: for these materials one additional elastic modulus, for example the shear modulus, is needed to determine wave speeds.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] It is possible to measure the bulk modulus using powder diffraction under applied pressure or at elevated temperatures, as well as by other methods for fluids, elastomers, minerals such as olivines, using theoretical calculations, of even granular materials such as sand grains.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] A material with a bulk modulus of 35 GPa loses one percent of its volume when subjected to an external pressure of 0.35 GPa (~3500 bar) (assumed constant or weakly pressure dependent bulk modulus).
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] Since linear elasticity is a direct result of interatomic interaction, it is related to the extension/compression of bonds.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] It can then be derived from the interatomic potential for crystalline materials.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] First, let us examine the potential energy of two interacting atoms.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] Starting from very far points, they will feel an attraction towards each other.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] As they approach each other, their potential energy will decrease.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] On the other hand, when two atoms are very close to each other, their total energy will be very high due to repulsive interaction.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] Together, these potentials guarantee an interatomic distance that achieves a minimal energy state.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] Where U is interatomic potential and r is the interatomic distance.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] This means the atoms are in equilibrium.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] To extend the two atoms approach into solid, consider a simple model, say, a 1-D array of one element with interatomic distance of r, and the equilibrium distance is *r*0.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] At equilibrium, the first derivative is 0, so the dominant term is the quadratic one.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] When displacement is small, the higher order terms should be omitted.
[src:compression-physics/bulk-modulus] This form can be easily extended to 3-D case, with volume per atom(Ω) in place of interatomic distance.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] There are four cases: either the substance remains a gas at standard temperature but increased pressure, the substance liquefies at standard temperature but increased pressure, the substance is dissolved in a solvent, or the substance is liquefied at reduced temperature and increased pressure.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] In the last case the bottle is constructed with an inner and outer shell separated by a vacuum (dewar flask) so that the low temperature can be maintained by evaporative cooling.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] The substance remains a *gas* at *standard temperature* and *increased pressure*, its critical temperature being below standard temperature.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] The substance *liquefies* at *standard temperature* but *increased pressure*.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] The substance is *dissolved* at *standard temperature* in a solvent.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] The substance is *liquefied* at *reduced temperature* and *increased pressure*.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] These are also referred to as cryogenic gases.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] The general rule is that one unit volume of liquid will expand to approximately 800 unit volumes of gas at standard temperature and pressure with some variation due to intermolecular force and molecule size compared to an ideal gas.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] Normal high pressure gas cylinders will hold gas at pressures from 200 to 400 bars (3,000 to 6,000 psi).
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] An ideal gas pressurised to 200 bar in a cylinder would contain 200 times as much as the volume of the cylinder at atmospheric pressure, but real gases will contain less than that by a few percent.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] At higher pressures, the shortfall is greater.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] Because the contents are under high pressure and are sometimes hazardous, there are special safety regulations for handling bottled gases.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] These include chaining bottles to prevent falling and breaking, proper ventilation to prevent injury or death in case of leaks and signage to indicate the potential hazards.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] In the United States, the Compressed Gas Association (CGA) sells a number of booklets and pamphlets on safe handling and use of bottled gases.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] (Members of the CGA can get the pamphlets for free.) The European Industrial Gases Association and the British Compressed Gases Association provide similar facilities in Europe and the United Kingdom.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] In the United States, 'bottled gas' typically refers to liquefied petroleum gas.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] 'Bottled gas' is sometimes used in medical supply, especially for portable oxygen tanks.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] Packaged industrial gases are frequently called 'cylinder gas', though 'bottled gas' is sometimes used.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] The United Kingdom and other parts of Europe more commonly refer to 'bottled gas' when discussing any usage whether industrial, medical or liquefied petroleum.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] However, in contrast, what the United States calls liquefied petroleum gas is known generically in the United Kingdom as 'LPG'; and it may be ordered using by one of several Trade names, or specifically as butane or propane depending on the required heat output.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] The user should not rely on the colour of a cylinder to indicate what it contains.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] The label or decal should always be checked for product identification.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] The colours below are specific shades, defined in the European Standard in terms of RAL coordinates.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] Diving cylinders are left unpainted (for aluminium), or painted to prevent corrosion (for steel), often in bright colors, most often fluorescent yellow, to increase visibility.
[src:compression-physics/compressed-gas] This should not be confused with industrial gases, where a yellow shoulder means chlorine.
[src:compression-physics/compression-member] A compression member is a structural element that primarily resists forces, which act to shorten or compress the member along its length.
[src:compression-physics/compression-member] Commonly found in engineering and architectural structures, such as columns, struts, and braces, compression members are designed to withstand loads that push or press on them without buckling or failing.
[src:compression-physics/compression-member] The behavior and strength of a compression member depends on factors like material properties, cross-sectional shape, length, and the type of loading applied.
[src:compression-physics/compression-member] These components are critical in frameworks like bridges, buildings, and towers, where they provide stability and support against vertical and lateral forces.
[src:compression-physics/compression-member] In buildings, posts and columns are almost always compression members, as are the *top chord* of trusses in bridges, etc.
[src:compression-physics/compression-member] For a compression member, such as a column, the principal stress primarily arises from axial forces, which act along a single axis, typically through the centroid of the member cross section.
[src:compression-physics/compression-member] Formulas for calculating the buckling strength of slender members were first developed by Euler, while equations like the Perry-Robertson formula are commonly applied to describe the behavior of intermediate members.
[src:compression-physics/compression-member] The Eurocodes published by the Comité Européen de Normalisation provide guidance of the calculation of strength for compression members in concrete, masonry, steel and timber.
[src:compression-physics/compression-member] There are other codes for steel compression members only.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] In mechanics, **compression** is the application of balanced inward ("pushing") forces to different points on a material or structure, that is, forces with no net sum or torque directed so as to reduce its size in one or more directions.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] It is contrasted with tension or traction, the application of balanced outward ("pulling") forces, and with shearing forces, directed so as to displace layers of the material parallel to each other.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] The compressive strength of materials and structures is an important engineering consideration.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] In **uniaxial compression**, the forces are directed along one direction only, so that they act towards decreasing the object's length along that direction.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] The compressive forces may also be applied in multiple directions; for example inwards along the edges of a plate or all over the side surface of a cylinder, so as to reduce its area (**biaxial compression**), or inwards over the entire surface of a body, so as to reduce its volume.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] Technically, a material is under a state of compression, at some specific point and along a specific direction x , if the normal component of the stress vector across a surface with normal direction x is directed opposite to x .
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] If the stress vector itself is opposite to x , the material is said to be under **normal compression** or **pure compressive stress** along x .
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] In a solid, the amount of compression generally depends on the direction x , and the material may be under compression along some directions but under traction along others.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] If the stress vector is purely compressive and has the same magnitude for all directions, the material is said to be under **isotropic compression**, **hydrostatic compression**, or **bulk compression**.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] This is the only type of static compression that liquids and gases can bear.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] It affects the volume of the material, as quantified by the bulk modulus and the volumetric strain.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] The inverse process of compression is called *decompression*, *dilation*, or *expansion*, in which the object enlarges or increases in volume.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] In a mechanical wave, which is longitudinal, the medium is displaced in the wave's direction, resulting in areas of compression and rarefaction.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] When put under compression (or any other type of stress), every material will suffer some deformation, even if imperceptible, that causes the average relative positions of its atoms and molecules to change.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] The deformation may be permanent, or may be reversed when the compression forces disappear.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] In the latter case, the deformation gives rise to reaction forces that oppose the compression forces, and may eventually balance them.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] Liquids and gases cannot bear steady uniaxial or biaxial compression, they will deform promptly and permanently and will not offer any permanent reaction force.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] However they can bear isotropic compression, and may be compressed in other ways momentarily, for instance in a sound wave.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] Every ordinary material will contract in volume when put under isotropic compression, contract in cross-section area when put under uniform biaxial compression, and contract in length when put into uniaxial compression.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] The deformation may not be uniform and may not be aligned with the compression forces.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] What happens in the directions where there is no compression depends on the material.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] Most materials will expand in those directions, but some special materials will remain unchanged or even contract.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] In general, the relation between the stress applied to a material and the resulting deformation is a central topic of continuum mechanics.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] Compression of solids has many implications in materials science, physics and structural engineering, for compression yields noticeable amounts of stress and tension.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] By inducing compression, mechanical properties such as compressive strength or modulus of elasticity, can be measured.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] Compression machines range from very small table top systems to ones with over 53 MN capacity.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] Gases are often stored and shipped in highly compressed form, to save space.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] Slightly compressed air or other gases are also used to fill balloons, rubber boats, and other inflatable structures.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] Compressed liquids are used in hydraulic equipment and in fracking.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] In internal combustion engines the explosive mixture gets compressed before it is ignited; the compression improves the efficiency of the engine.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] In the Otto cycle, for instance, the second stroke of the piston effects the compression of the charge which has been drawn into the cylinder by the first forward stroke.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] The term is applied to the arrangement by which the exhaust valve of a steam engine is made to close, shutting a portion of the exhaust steam in the cylinder, before the stroke of the piston is quite complete.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] This steam being compressed as the stroke is completed, a cushion is formed against which the piston does work while its velocity is being rapidly reduced, and thus the stresses in the mechanism due to the inertia of the reciprocating parts are lessened.
[src:compression-physics/compression-physics] This compression, moreover, obviates the shock which would otherwise be caused by the admission of the fresh steam for the return stroke.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In mechanics, **compressive strength** (or **compression strength**) is the capacity of a material or structure to withstand loads tending to reduce size (compression).
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] It is opposed to *tensile strength*, which withstands loads tending to elongate, resisting tension (being pulled apart).
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In the study of strength of materials, compressive strength, tensile strength, and shear strength can be analyzed independently.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Some materials fracture at their compressive strength limit; others deform irreversibly, so a given amount of deformation may be considered as the limit for compressive load.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Compressive strength is a key value for design of structures.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Compressive strength is often measured on a universal testing machine.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Measurements of compressive strength are affected by the specific test method and conditions of measurement.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Compressive strengths are usually reported in relationship to a specific technical standard.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] When a specimen of material is loaded in such a way that it extends it is said to be in *tension*.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] On the other hand, if the material compresses and shortens it is said to be in *compression*.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] On an atomic level, molecules or atoms are forced together when in compression, whereas they are pulled apart when in tension.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Since atoms in solids always try to find an equilibrium position, and distance between other atoms, forces arise throughout the entire material which oppose both tension or compression.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The phenomena prevailing on an atomic level are therefore similar.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The "strain" is the relative change in length under applied stress; positive strain characterizes an object under tension load which tends to lengthen it, and a compressive stress that shortens an object gives negative strain.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Tension tends to pull small sideways deflections back into alignment, while compression tends to amplify such deflection into buckling.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Compressive strength is measured on materials, components, and structures.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The ultimate compressive strength of a material is the maximum uniaxial compressive stress that it can withstand before complete failure.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] This value is typically determined through a compressive test conducted using a universal testing machine.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] During the test, a steadily increasing uniaxial compressive load is applied to the test specimen until it fails.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The specimen, often cylindrical in shape, experiences both axial shortening and lateral expansion under the load.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The compressive strength of the material corresponds to the stress at the red point shown on the curve.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In a compression test, there is a linear region where the material follows Hooke's law.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Hence, for this region, $\sigma =E\varepsilon ,$ where, this time, E refers to the Young's modulus for compression.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In this region, the material deforms elastically and returns to its original length when the stress is removed.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] This linear region terminates at what is known as the yield point.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Above this point the material behaves plastically and will not return to its original length once the load is removed.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] There is a difference between the engineering stress and the true stress.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] ${\acute {\sigma }}={\frac {F}{A}},$ where F is load applied [N] and A is area [m2].
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] As stated, the area of the specimen varies on compression.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In reality therefore the area is some function of the applied load i.e.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Indeed, stress is defined as the force divided by the area at the start of the experiment.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] This is known as the engineering stress, and is defined by $\sigma _{e}={\frac {F}{A_{0}}},$ where *A*0 is the original specimen area [m2].
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Correspondingly, the engineering strain is defined by $\varepsilon _{e}={\frac {l-l_{0}}{l_{0}}},$ where l is the current specimen length [m] and *l*0 is the original specimen length [m].
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] where *F** is the load applied just before crushing and *l** is the specimen length just before crushing.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] When a uniaxial compressive load is applied to an object it will become shorter and spread laterally so its original cross sectional area ( ${\textstyle A_{o}}$ ) increases to the loaded area ( ${\textstyle A}$ ).
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Thus the true stress ( ${\acute {\sigma }}=F/A$ ) deviates from engineering stress ( $\sigma _{e}=F/A_{o}$ ).
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Tests that measure the engineering stress at the point of failure in a material are often sufficient for many routine applications, such as quality control in concrete production.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] However, determining the true stress in materials under compressive loads is important for research focused on the properties on new materials and their processing.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The geometry of test specimens and friction can significantly influence the results of compressive stress tests.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Friction at the contact points between the testing machine and the specimen can restrict the lateral expansion at its ends (also known as 'barreling') leading to non-uniform stress distribution.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] This is discussed in section on contact with friction.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] This condition represents an ideal test condition.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] For all practical purposes the volume of a high bulk modulus material (e.g. solid metals) is not changed by uniaxial compression.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] So $Al=A_{o}l_{o}$ Using the strain equation from above $A=A_{o}/(1+\epsilon _{e})$ and ${\acute {\sigma }}=\sigma _{e}(1+\epsilon _{e})$ Note that compressive strain is negative, so the true stress ( ${\acute {\sigma }}$ ) is less than the engineering stress ( ${\textstyle \sigma _{e}}$ ).
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The true strain ( ${\acute {\epsilon }}$ ) can be used in these formulas instead of engineering strain ( ${\textstyle \epsilon _{e}}$ ) when the deformation is large.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] As the load is applied, friction at the interface between the specimen and the test machine restricts the lateral expansion at its ends.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Round test specimens made from ductile materials with a high bulk modulus, such as metals, tend to form a barrel shape under axial compressive loading due to frictional contact at the ends.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] is the maximum loaded diameter of the test specimen.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Note that if there is frictionless contact between the ends of the specimen and the test machine, the bulge radius becomes infinite ( ${\textstyle R=\infty }$ ) and ${\textstyle C=1}$ .
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In this case, the formulas yield the same result as ${\textstyle {\acute {\sigma }}=\sigma _{e}(1+\epsilon _{e})}$ because ${\textstyle \sigma _{a}}$ changes according to the ratio $(d_{o}/d_{2})^{2}$ .
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The parameters ( ${\textstyle F,d_{1},d_{2},l}$ ) obtained from a test result can be used with these formulas to calculate the equivalent true stress ${\textstyle {\acute {\sigma }}}$ at failure.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The graph of specimen shape effect shows how the ratio of true stress to engineering stress (σ´/σe) varies with the aspect ratio of the test specimen ( ${\textstyle d_{o}/l_{o}}$ ).
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The curves were calculated using the formulas provided above, based on the specific values presented in the table for specimen shape effect calculations.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] For the curves where end restraint is applied to the specimens, they are assumed to be fully laterally restrained, meaning that the coefficient of friction at the contact points between the specimen and the testing machine is greater than or equal to one (μ ⩾ 1).
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] As shown in the section on correction formulas, as the length of test specimens is increased and their aspect ratio approaches zero ( $d_{o}/l_{o}\longrightarrow 0$ ), the compressive stresses (σ) approach the true value (σ′).
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] However, conducting tests with excessively long specimens is impractical, as they would fail by buckling before reaching the material's true compressive strength.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] To overcome this, a series of tests can be conducted using specimens with varying aspect ratios, and the true compressive strength can then be determined through extrapolation.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Concrete and ceramics typically have much higher compressive strengths than tensile strengths.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Composite materials, such as glass fiber epoxy matrix composite, tend to have higher tensile strengths than compressive strengths.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Metals are difficult to test to failure in tension vs compression.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In compression metals fail from buckling/crumbling/45° shear which is much different (though higher stresses) than tension which fails from defects or necking down.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] There are various modes of ductile failure for structural members in compression.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The most common is Flexural Buckling, where the member will bend outward without initially fracturing.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] This failure mode depends on the slenderness ratio, a ratio between the effective length of the member and the radius of gyration.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Another common ductile failure mode for compression members is yielding.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Compressive yielding occurs in members with a low slenderness ratio, meaning they are short and wide.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Other possible compressive failure modes for ductile materials, include local buckling, where only part of the member fails, flexural-torsional buckling, where a member both twists and buckles laterally, and torsional buckling where the member only twists and does not move laterally.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] A brittle material in compression typically will fail by axial splitting, shear fracture, or ductile failure depending on the level of constraint in the direction perpendicular to the direction of loading.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] If there is no constraint (also called confining pressure), the brittle material is likely to fail by axial splitting.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Moderate confining pressure often results in shear fracture, while high confining pressure often leads to ductile failure, even in brittle materials.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Axial Splitting relieves elastic energy in brittle material by releasing strain energy in the directions perpendicular to the applied compressive stress.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] As defined by a materials Poisson ratio a material compressed elastically in one direction will strain in the other two directions.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] During axial splitting a crack may release that tensile strain by forming a new surface parallel to the applied load.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The material then proceeds to separate in two or more pieces.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Hence the axial splitting occurs most often when there is no confining pressure, i.e. a lesser compressive load on axis perpendicular to the main applied load.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The material now split into micro columns will feel different frictional forces either due to inhomogeneity of interfaces on the free end or stress shielding.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In the case of stress shielding, inhomogeneity in the materials can lead to different Young's modulus.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] This will in turn cause the stress to be disproportionately distributed, leading to a difference in frictional forces.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In either case this will cause the material sections to begin bending and lead to ultimate failure.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Microcracks are a leading cause of failure under compression for brittle and quasi-brittle materials.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Sliding along crack tips leads to tensile forces along the tip of the crack.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Microcracks tend to form around any pre-existing crack tips.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In all cases it is the overall global compressive stress interacting with local microstructural anomalies to create local areas of tension.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Microcracks can stem from a few factors.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Stiff inclusions within a material such as a precipitate can cause localized areas of tension.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] (b) When inclusions are grouped up or larger, this effect can be amplified.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Even without pores or stiff inclusions, a material can develop microcracks between weak inclined (relative to applied stress) interfaces.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] These interfaces can slip and create a secondary crack.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] These secondary cracks can continue opening, as the slip of the original interfaces keeps opening the secondary crack (c).
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The slipping of interfaces alone is not solely responsible for secondary crack growth as inhomogeneities in the material's Young's modulus can lead to an increase in effective misfit strain.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Cracks that grow this way are known as wingtip microcracks.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The growth of microcracks is not the growth of the original crack or imperfection.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The cracks that nucleate do so perpendicular to the original crack and are known as secondary cracks.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The figure below emphasizes this point for wingtip cracks.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] These secondary cracks can grow to as long as 10–15 times the length of the original cracks in simple (uniaxial) compression.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] However, if a transverse compressive load is applied.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The growth is limited to a few integer multiples of the original crack's length.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] If the sample size is large enough such that the worse defect's secondary cracks cannot grow large enough to break the sample, other defects within the sample will begin to grow secondary cracks as well.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] This will occur homogeneously over the entire sample.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] These micro-cracks form an echelon that can form an "intrinsic" fracture behavior, the nucleus of a shear fault instability.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Eventually this leads the material deforming non-homogeneously.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] That is the strain caused by the material will no longer vary linearly with the load.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Creating localized shear bands on which the material will fail according to deformation theory.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] For designers, compressive strength is one of the most important engineering properties of concrete.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] It is standard industrial practice that the compressive strength of a given concrete mix is classified by grade.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Cubic or cylindrical samples of concrete are tested under a compression testing machine to measure this value.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Test requirements vary by country based on their differing design codes.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The compressive strength of concrete is given in terms of the characteristic compressive strength of 150 mm size cubes tested after 28 days (fck).
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In field, compressive strength tests are also conducted at interim duration i.e. after 7 days to verify the anticipated compressive strength expected after 28 days.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The same is done to be forewarned of an event of failure and take necessary precautions.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The **characteristic strength** is defined as the **strength** of the **concrete** below which not more than 5% of the test results are expected to fall.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] For design purposes, this compressive strength value is restricted by dividing with a factor of safety, whose value depends on the design philosophy used.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] The construction industry is often involved in a wide array of testing.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] In addition to simple compression testing, testing standards such as ASTM C39, ASTM C109, ASTM C469, ASTM C1609 are among the test methods that can be followed to measure the mechanical properties of concrete.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] When measuring the compressive strength and other material properties of concrete, testing equipment that can be manually controlled or servo-controlled may be selected depending on the procedure followed.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Certain test methods specify or limit the loading rate to a certain value or a range, whereas other methods request data based on test procedures run at very low rates.
[src:compression-physics/compressive-strength] Ultra-high performance concrete (UHPC) is defined as having a compressive strength over 150 MPa.
